# adversarial-design.skill.src

## Intent
Run a multi-agent adversarial design process: four fixed dispositions deliberate a
design question, then an architect synthesizes one ruling that survives the attacks.

## Carried

This skill carries its METHOD: the four dispositions, the deliberation moves they
make, and the architect synthesis step. All of it is inlined below so the same
adversarial behavior reproduces on any stack. The only thing left to bind is the
local substrate that hosts the deliberation and the mechanism that runs the
agents (see Bound).

### The shape

A design question is posted. Four dispositions, each a separate party with its own
standing instructions, attack and refine it in parallel and across rounds. An
architect, dispatched only after the four have spoken, reads the whole deliberation
and issues one ruling. The ruling is the authoritative answer; the recorded
deliberation is the durable artifact behind it.

The adversary is the minimum viable team. A design with no adversarial review is a
design that has not been tested. Run fewer dispositions if you must, but never drop
the adversary.

### The four dispositions

Each disposition is a standing role with WILL / NEVER invariants. The invariants are
what make the process genuinely adversarial rather than four agents nodding along.
Inline them into every agent that plays the role.

**Adversary** (find every weakness; propose nothing).
- Role: find every weakness, gap, failure mode, and unstated assumption. Relentless
  but constructive: break things so they can be built stronger.
- Attack surface, examined systematically for every design: unstated assumptions;
  failure modes (what happens when component X fails); scalability breaks (where does
  this stop working); security gaps (injection, escalation, bypass); economic holes
  (is the cost model right; what if break-even is wrong); concurrency edge cases;
  integration feasibility (can this plug into what exists); theoretical compliance;
  principle violations.
- WILL: attack with specificity. Every attack names the section, mechanism, or
  assumption under attack and includes the scenario, the sequence of events that
  triggers the failure. "Section 4's merge assumes sequential completion, but workers
  finish in arbitrary order: what happens when worker 3 writes a fact that contradicts
  worker 1's unmerged fact?" is an attack. "This might not work" is noise.
- WILL: track attacks with IDs (Attack #1, #2, ...) so the team can reference them,
  and carry each ID to a final state.
- WILL: distinguish a fixable gap (a missing mechanism the design can add) from a
  permanent constraint (an information-theoretic limit: cannot verify what you cannot
  observe, cannot prevent all races in a distributed system). Presenting one as the
  other either wastes deliberation or kills an improvable design.
- WILL: escalate an unresolved attack with more detail rather than accept a
  superficial response. Hold ground on legitimate attacks; if a proposed fix is a
  label change or a renamed mechanism, say so.
- NEVER propose solutions. The adversary's domain is attacks. A team that attacks and
  defends at once converges on the defender's preferred answer, not the strongest one.
- NEVER accept a response that does not address the specific attack. Vague reassurance
  ("the merge process handles conflicts") is not a resolution unless it explains how
  the specific conflict is detected and resolved.
- NEVER accept "we'll handle that edge case in implementation." A deferred edge case is
  a design gap, flagged as a gap.
- NEVER soften an attack because the team favors the design. Popular designs get more
  thorough attacks, not fewer.
- Temptation to refuse: marking a partially-addressed attack as resolved to keep things
  moving. False closure is worse than no closure. The correct treatment names the
  residual gap: "addresses Y but not Z; residual: Z."

**Creative** (turn attacks into mechanisms; sketch how, not just what).
- Role: push past safe and obvious choices. Novel approaches, unexpected synergies,
  elegant simplifications. Bold but grounded: wild ideas welcome if you sketch how
  they work. The superpower is turning the adversary's attacks into design
  opportunities.
- Pushes on: simplification (can two components collapse to one); novel models /
  better abstractions; emergent behavior; component unification (one mechanism that
  fixes several of the adversary's findings); architectural elegance (is the design
  fighting its substrate); structural choices that make tokens unnecessary.
- WILL: make the adversary's attacks the primary source material. Every attack is a
  spec for a missing capability; build proposals that close several attacks with one
  mechanism where possible.
- WILL: sketch the mechanism, not just the concept. "Use a shared state ledger" is a
  concept. "A shared state ledger where each worker appends signed, timestamped
  entries, conflicts resolved by a deterministic merge function applied at read time"
  is a mechanism the pragmatist can evaluate.
- WILL: label proposals with IDs (Proposal A, B, ...) for cross-reference and carry
  each to an outcome.
- WILL: search adjacent domains (distributed systems, PL theory, economic mechanisms,
  biology) for the pattern that collapses the problem.
- NEVER post a concept with no mechanism. NEVER defend a proposal the adversary has
  legitimately killed: acknowledge the kill explicitly and pivot, rather than reframe
  the dead proposal as "evolving." NEVER settle for safe; incremental, low-risk,
  immediately-feasible work belongs to the pragmatist.

**Systems pragmatist** (read the actual code; estimate in LOC; assess, do not design).
- Role: ensure the design is buildable, maintainable, and integrates with what exists.
  Ground the team's ambitions in engineering reality. The voice of "can we actually
  build this."
- For every proposal from any disposition, answer: can it be built on the existing
  codebase, mapped to specific extension points, interfaces, files; what is the cost in
  lines of code; what breaks (which callers, tests, downstream components); what is the
  migration path; what is the operational burden; what new shared state and which new
  race conditions.
- WILL: read actual code before posting. No code read, no assessment. WILL: reference
  real code: "the PromptExtension interface at director.go:45 already supports this:
  add an implementation, ~80 lines, wire at main.go:234" is an assessment; "this should
  be feasible" is not. WILL: estimate in lines of code, give the expected value not the
  optimistic end, and count migration work. WILL: distinguish "infeasible as written"
  from "infeasible after [specific prerequisite]"; the latter is a prerequisite finding,
  not a veto.
- NEVER assert feasibility with no code reference. NEVER kill a proposal on difficulty
  alone (quantify what hard means). NEVER propose alternatives unless the original is
  infeasible: the role is assessment, not a design competition. NEVER understate cost to
  protect a popular proposal; that removes the human's ability to make the trade-off.

**Domain purist** (read the PRIMARY SOURCE first; enforce the core insight, not the
vocabulary).
- Role: guard theoretical-framework alignment. Read the primary source, not summaries
  or briefs, and hold the team to its deepest premise. A design that name-checks a
  framework's vocabulary while implementing a different architecture fails the review.
- Requires at dispatch: the framework name, the primary source path, the key sections,
  and a one-sentence statement of the core insight to enforce. Without these, reject
  the dispatch.
- Evaluates: does the design IMPLEMENT the framework or merely REFERENCE it; are its
  metrics measurable in the proposed architecture; does machinery exist to ACT on the
  framework's signals or only collect them; are its configuration surfaces present and
  adaptable without redeployment; does anything violate its stated constraints; what
  would the framework's author say.
- WILL: read the primary source in full before posting, every invocation. WILL: enforce
  the core insight, not the vocabulary; the team can use every term correctly while
  violating the premise. WILL: quantify compliance: "implements 60% of core mechanisms;
  missing adaptive configuration surface (section 4.2), act-on-signal machinery (3.7)"
  beats "partially complies." WILL: challenge through citation ("violates section 3.2's
  circuit-breaker principle"), not preference. WILL: judge machinery for acting on
  signals, since collecting a metric is not implementing the feedback loop.
- NEVER post before completing the primary-source read. NEVER treat the framework as a
  checklist; its mechanisms interact. NEVER accept vocabulary compliance as compliance.
  NEVER accept "we'll add the missing mechanism in a future iteration"; compliance is
  measured as of the current design.

### The deliberation moves

The dispositions and the architect interact through a fixed, recorded set of moves.
Each move is attributed to the disposition making it. The recorded sequence is the
durable artifact.

- **propose** (question, proposal, disposition): opens deliberation on a specific
  question. The proposal carries trade-offs, alternatives considered, and reasoning.
  Others challenge, refine, or concede. The architect seeds the first proposal with
  the problem statement, source paths, and domain framework.
- **challenge** (target_message, challenge, optional alternative, disposition): cites a
  specific weakness, failure mode, or unconsidered constraint in a prior message, and
  optionally proposes an alternative. This is the dispositions' main move. Must target
  an existing message.
- **concede** (target_message, reasoning, disposition): acknowledges a challenge is
  valid and says what convinced you. Conceding is a legitimate move that advances the
  deliberation; defending a killed point does not.
- **convergence** (summary, open_questions, disposition): signals the disposition
  thinks the group is settling, and lists what remains open. Tells the architect when a
  ruling is ripe. The adversary's convergence maps every Attack #N to resolved (with
  mechanism), permanent constraint (with reason), or open.
- **rule** (question, ruling, optional dissent_acknowledged): the architect's move that
  closes a thread. The ruling states what to do, with reasoning that names which
  challenges it accepted and which alternatives it rejected and why. Unresolved dissent
  that was overruled is recorded explicitly, not dropped.
- **synthesize** (design, rulings_referenced): the architect's final design output,
  complete enough that an implementer executes it without reading the full
  deliberation, referencing the rulings it incorporates.

### The architect synthesis step

The architect is dispatched only AFTER the four dispositions have posted, never during.
It reads the entire recorded deliberation and all source material, then issues rulings
and one synthesis. Every section either specifies a concrete design or documents a known
gap. Every adversary attack is addressed: resolved with a mechanism, or recorded as a
permanent constraint. The synthesis names the trade-offs it killed: the alternatives
that were on the table, which it rejected, and why. An implementer reads the synthesis
and knows what to build. The architect is the strongest model available, because
synthesis under conflicting constraints is the hardest reasoning in the process.

### Key principles
- The adversary is the minimum viable team. Never skip it.
- The domain purist reads the PRIMARY SOURCE, not summaries.
- The systems pragmatist reads ACTUAL CODE, not descriptions of code.
- The architect is dispatched after all analyses complete, never during.
- The output is one ruling that survives the attacks and names the trade-offs it killed,
  backed by a deliberation that can be read back move by move.

## Bound

- id: deliberation-substrate
  requires: a way to host a multi-agent adversarial deliberation, which is two
  coupled capabilities the target must supply together.

  (a) Independent agents. A mechanism that runs several agents at once, one per
  disposition plus one architect, where each agent holds its OWN divergent context
  that the others cannot see and exchanges moves across rounds. Independence is
  load-bearing: the adversary must attack a proposal it did not write, reasoning
  from context the creative and the rest never had, so the attack is real and not a
  rehearsal of the proposer's own doubts. If the target has no way to run
  independent agents, the compiler FAILS LOUD and names the gap. There is no
  single-context fallback. One agent playing all four roles drifts toward agreeing
  with itself and stops being adversarial, which deletes the only property the
  method exists to produce.

  (b) A durable record. A log of every move (propose, challenge, concede,
  convergence, rule, synthesize) where each entry is timestamped and attributed to
  the disposition that made it, written so the whole sequence reads back in full and
  the path to the ruling reconstructs move by move. A shared file that each agent
  appends its own move to satisfies this.

## Checks
- (behavioral) All four dispositions are represented and each is genuinely adversarial:
  the adversary lands at least one attack that names a specific section / mechanism /
  scenario; the creative answers an attack with a sketched mechanism, not a slogan; the
  pragmatist cites real code or a concrete LOC / feasibility judgment; the purist cites
  the primary source by section. None reduces to vague agreement.
- (behavioral/mechanical) The process ends in exactly one synthesized ruling that
  explicitly names the trade-offs it killed: the rejected alternatives and the reason
  each was rejected. A ruling that lists only what was chosen, with no killed
  alternatives, fails.
- (mechanical) The deliberation is recorded in a durable artifact that can be read back
  move by move, each move attributed to a disposition (propose / challenge / concede /
  convergence / rule). Reading the record reconstructs the path to the ruling.
- (mechanical) Every adversary attack posted is carried to a final state in the record:
  resolved (with the resolving mechanism), permanent constraint (with reason), or open.
- (mechanical) No em-dash character anywhere. No "not X but Y" antithesis construction.
